  "prompt": "Can mechanical engineers do the work of chemical engineers?",
  "response": "While mechanical and chemical engineers have some overlapping skills, they cannot fully substitute for each other due to significant differences in their specialized knowledge and training:\n\nMechanical Engineers typically:\n- Design mechanical systems and machines\n- Work with materials and structural design\n- Focus on motion, force, and energy transfer\n- Use tools like CAD and stress analysis software\n\nChemical Engineers typically:\n- Design chemical processes and reactions\n- Work with chemical transformations\n- Focus on chemical processing and reactions\n- Have deep knowledge of chemistry and thermodynamics\n- Specialize in process design for chemical plants\n\nKey differences:\n- Chemical engineers understand complex chemical reactions\n- Chemical engineers have specialized chemistry knowledge\n- Chemical engineers are trained in specific process design techniques\n- Mechanical engineers lack detailed chemical processing expertise\n\nWhile there might be some overlap in general engineering principles, each discipline requires specific technical knowledge that is not easily interchangeable. A mechanical engineer would need significant additional training to perform a chemical engineer's specialized tasks, and vice versa.\n\nIn collaborative settings, they often work together, but they do not directly replace each other's core professional responsibilities.",
